Can the euro be fixed?
Paris—Recently, Germany's finance minister, Wolfgang Schaeuble, has brought the option of Greece leaving the euro onto the table, hoping to send a signal that no member state can be exempt from the strict discipline of the monetary union.
In fact, his proposal has sparked a big debate about the principles that form the basis of the euro, the governance model of the euro, and the rationale for the existence of the euro.
Two weeks before Schaeuble's proposal, European leaders had already noted a report on the future of the euro written by European Commission President Jean-Claude Juncker and his colleagues from other EU institutions. However, the new debate over Greece has led many policymakers to believe it is necessary to return to the original starting point.
At the same time, citizens are questioning why they should share a common currency?
Does this make sense? Can there be a consensus on the future of Greece?
Currency is like a nation; it requires a myth to establish it.
Traditional wisdom holds that the euro was the political price Germany paid to reunify with France.
In fact, Germany's reunification was just the final step of an engineering project that had already taken shape in the 1980s to resolve a long-standing problem.
European governments strongly opposed floating exchange rates, considering them incompatible with a single market; at the same time, they were unwilling to maintain a monetary system dominated by the German central bank in the long term.
A truly European currency based on German principles seems to be the best solution.
In hindsight, Germany's reunification was more of a curse than a blessing.
When exchange rates were locked in 1999, Germany was overvalued and its economy was struggling; France was undervalued and its economy was thriving.
In the following decade, the imbalance gradually re-emerged between the resurgent Germany and countries experiencing credit booms due to low interest rates.
And with the outbreak of the global financial crisis in 2008, these conditions became the breeding ground for a perfect storm.
No one knows what Europe would be like without the euro.
Will the fixed exchange rate system continue or collapse?
Will the German mark remain overvalued?
Will countries reintroduce trade barriers and end the single market?
Will a real estate bubble emerge in Spain?
Will government reforms be more or less?
It is impossible to establish a baseline for reverse analysis to assess the impact of the euro.
But this is certainly not a reason for complacency.
In the past 15 years, the performance of the eurozone economy has been disappointing, and its political institutions must bear the responsibility.
What is truly important is whether a common European currency remains significant for the future.
This issue is often avoided because the cost of leaving the euro is unimaginably high (and if the eurozone were to collapse during a crisis, exacerbating mutual tensions among member states, the costs would be further increased).
Moreover, abolishing the euro could unleash the dark forces of nationalism and protectionism.
However, Kevin O’Rourke from Oxford University recently pointed out that this argument is not sufficient.
Logically, this is equivalent to suggesting that a couple should stay married simply because the cost of divorce is too high.
So, does the euro still make sense?
Originally, people expected the euro to bring three major economic benefits.
People assumed that a currency union could promote economic integration and consolidate long-term growth in Europe.
On the contrary, trade and investment growth within the eurozone has been lackluster, and the growth potential has actually weakened.
This is partly because national governments have not moved forward on the basis of monetary union to build the eurozone into an economic superpower, but instead have tried to retain the remaining power they still had.
This might be politically logical, but it is economically worthless: Europe's huge internal market is one of its main assets, so the opportunity to strengthen the internal market must never be wasted.
Secondly, people hoped that the euro would become one of the major international currencies (especially considering that few countries could meet the necessary legal, market, and policy institutions).
According to the latest data from the European Central Bank, this hope has basically been realized.
The international use of the euro ranks second only to the dollar, an achievement that helps Europe continue to influence the global economic order rather than becoming an irrelevant entity.
Thirdly, people (not without naivety) believed that the institutions based on the euro could improve the overall quality of economic policy, as if the overall policy level of Europe were naturally higher than that of national policies.
After the global financial crisis of 2008, a severe test arrived: the eurozone overestimated the fiscal dimension of the crisis and underestimated its financial dimension, so its performance was worse than that of the United States and the United Kingdom.
If the euro is to bring prosperity, further policy institutional reforms are necessary.
However, formulating and implementing a schedule requires a broad consensus on the nature of the problems.
The ongoing debate over Greece indicates that Europe is far from reaching an agreement: member countries have conflicting analyses of the root causes of the debt crisis, and therefore also have conflicting remedies.
Richard Cooper from Harvard University once observed that in the early stages of international public health cooperation, global disease governance was greatly hindered by different transmission patterns in various countries.
Countries all favor joint action, but they cannot form a unified plan because they disagree on how infectious diseases spread from one country to another.
This is the problem the eurozone faces today.
Luckily, this problem is not unsolvable, as major reforms such as the establishment of the European Stability Mechanism (ESM) and the launch of the banking union have proven.
Inconsistencies have not prevented the European Central Bank from taking decisive action, indicating that institutional governance does indeed matter.
However, the fact that reforms and actions only began recently and were implemented under the pressure of a severe crisis has made us clearly aware of the difficulty in reaching a consensus.
Europe can no longer procrastinate or pretend any longer.
Member states of the eurozone must form a consistent agenda regarding governance and political reforms, transforming the monetary union into an engine of prosperity. Otherwise, they will continue to sink into repeated debates and crises until citizens lose patience or the market loses confidence.
Clarity is a prerequisite for serious discussions and major reforms.
Today, all major stakeholders have an obligation to clearly define what they consider indispensable, what they cannot accept, and what they are prepared to offer in exchange for what they want.
